  "summary": "Following Detective Good's suggestion that a boy's comment regarding Russians might be significant, Chief Inspector Huishe decides to question Tina Aghill regarding her red bubble car. Huishe confronts Tina, noting that although she previously claimed to have stayed home all evening, evidence places her car near Sunset Corner just before seven o'clock on the night of her mother's murder. Tina admits she drove to the location but claims she changed her mind and did not enter the house. Despite Huishe's accusation that she is withholding information to protect a family member—possibly her brother Michael—Tina maintains she saw and heard nothing.\n\nLater, Dr. Calgary meets with Huishe to gather information about the Aghill case, expressing a sense of responsibility for the trouble caused. Huishe describes Jacqueline Aghill as a small-time criminal with a history of embezzlement and scamming middle-aged or elderly women by feigning romantic interest; he notes these women rarely report such crimes to avoid embarrassment. Calgary also inquires about the eldest daughter of the family, Mrs. Darlant. He mentions that he was unable to visit her because her house was locked and her family claimed that she and her husband were out.",
